      "title": "Service Layer pattern: CategoryService + IngredientService implementation",
      "content": "**What**: Extracted CategoryService and IngredientService from routers to implement Repository + UoW + Service Layer pattern consistently across Categoría, Ingrediente, and Producto modules.\n\n**Why**: Categoría and Ingrediente had business logic directly in endpoints (architectural debt). This refactor aligns them with Producto's proven pattern: clean separation between HTTP concerns (routers) and business logic (services).\n\n**Where**: \n- backend/services/categoria_service.py (160 lines)\n- backend/services/ingrediente_service.py (280 lines)\n- backend/routers/categorias.py (refactored to 224 lines)\n- backend/routers/ingredientes.py (refactored to 298 lines)\n- repositories/producto_repository.py (added count_by_category, count_by_ingredient methods)\n\n**Learned**: \n1. **Validation in services, not routers**: Services validate and raise ValueError(\"specific message\"). Routers catch and map to HTTP (409 if \"ya existe\", 404 if \"no existe\", 400 otherwise).\n2. **UoW ownership checks**: Use `uow.productos.count_by_category(id)` to verify before soft-delete, not direct product queries.\n3. **Consistent exception messages**: Message pattern determines HTTP status (\"ya existe\" → 409 Conflict, \"no existe\" → 404 Not Found, \"en uso\" → 409 Conflict).\n4. **Service method signature**: All services follow (self, uow), receive UoW as dependency, commit explicitly after mutations.\n5. **Testing strategy**: Unit tests use mocks (mock UoW), integration tests use real UoW. No FastAPI mocking needed for service tests.\n6. **Docstring discipline**: Every method must document: what it does, parameters, return type, exceptions raised (and what they map to in HTTP).\n7. **API contract preservation**: Refactored endpoints return IDENTICAL responses and error codes as before - this is testable.",
